    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Dasyatis brevicaudata</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_3185",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Head and body form an enormous, flattened, angular disc. Dorsal fins absent. Tail unusually short (less than length of body) relative to other regional stingrays and bears a large, venomous stinging spine projecting from its dorsal surface and scattered small denticles (densest towards tip). Upper surface plain brown, with row of small, white pores along bases of pectoral fins. Underside white with conspicuous gill slits.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_3186",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 300 cm disc width and 430 cm total length (including tail) and with a mass of up to 300 kg.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_3187",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Southern Africa, Australia and New Zealand.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to Maputo.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_3188",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Thought to be the largest of all stingrays and can be distinguished from other local species by its enormous size and shorter tail. Found over soft substrata from shallow water to a depth of at least 480 m. Although curious and not aggressive should be approached with caution, as the sting can be over 30 cm long and can inflict a dangerous wound.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_3189",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Feeds on both benthic invertebrates, such as mollusks and crustaceans, as well as fish. Can use suction to extract buried prey, the excess water then being expelled though the gill slits. Has been observed patrolling beds of chokka squid eggs during mass spawnings, feeding on squid that come to the bottom to lay.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_3190",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Undertakes courtship behaviour in mid-water, males following females and attempting to grip and bite her disc. When she agrees to mate the male rolls upside down and inserts his clasper into her vent. Captive females have been observed mating with up to three males in succession.&nbsp;Give birth to 6-10 live pups with disc widths of 32-36 cm.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_3191",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The very large size, relative lack of patterning and short tail distinguish this species from other regional stingrays</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_3192",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
